<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
FLORIDA; 
</P>
<P>
WEATHER POSTPONES ATLAS ROCKET LIFTOFF 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and Wire reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The threat of severe thunderstorms at Cape Canaveral, Fla., forced another 
postponement of the launch of a newly repaired Atlas rocket with a government 
satellite aboard. 
</P>
<P>
The first launch attempt, on Friday, was called off because of a helium leak, 
but the part that caused the problem has been replaced, officials said. The 
launch was rescheduled for 3:26 p.m. EDT today, but hopes were not high for a 
blastoff because the weather outlook appeared to be about the same. The Atlas 1 
rocket, making its commercial debut, was to boost the Combined Release and 
Radiation Effects Satellite into an elliptical orbit. 
</P>
