<HEADLINE>
<P>
2-TIME LOSER WINS HEMINGWAY CONTEST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
KEY WEST, Fla. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The third time proved to be the charm for a Longboat Key man who won top honors 
Sunday in the Ernest Hemingway Look-Alike Contest, part of Key West's 10th 
annual tribute to the Nobel Prize-winning author. 
</P>
<P>
Fred Burnham, competing for a third consecutive year, attributed the victory to 
his having raised a shaggy, gray beard reminiscent of the late novelist's. 
</P>
<P>
"The first year I didn't even qualify (for the finals)," said Burnham, who owns 
a construction cleanup firm. "But the comaraderie and good times kept me coming 
back." 
</P>
<P>
The 63 Hemingway look-alikes, from as far away as Santa Rosa, Calif., competed 
"head to head" for three days at Sloppy Joe's, which bills itself as 
Hemingway's favorite bar on Key West. 
</P>
<P>
While living on Key West in the 1930s, Hemingway produced some of his most 
famous works, including "For Whom the Bell Tolls," "A Farewell to Arms," "The 
Snows of Kilimanjaro" and "Green Hills of Africa." 
</P>
<P>
To honor Hemingway's literary genius, each year the festival includes a short 
story writing competition. "If You Can Hear This," by Pamela Ball, of 
Tallahassee, this year took top honors out of 620 entries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, The Importance of Looking Like Ernest: A Florida man won top honors in 
the Ernest Hemingway Look-Alike Contest, part of Key West's 10th annual tribute 
to the Nobel Prize-winning author who once lived there. Fred Burnham -- above 
left, being congratulated by another competitor -- credited his new shaggy 
beard for the victory. United Press International 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
