<HEADLINE>
<P>
IT'S A FAMILY AFFAIR AT FIREHOUSE; 2 GENERATIONS TAKE UP THE BATTLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BOB SCHWARTZ, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In their 31 years with the Los Angeles County Fire Department, Emmett and John 
Kinney have seen it all: brush fires, industrial fires, house fires, the Watts 
Riot fires and untold accidents and crime scenes. 
</P>
<P>
But on Sunday, the two brothers did something they'd never done before. They 
worked in Willowbrook's Fire Station 41 with two of Emmett's sons, bringing 
four Kinney firefighters together on one shift. 
</P>
<P>
"I'm going to be out of here in a short time," said station Capt. John Kinney, 
who plans to retire next year. "We wanted to do this before that happens." 
</P>
<P>
John Kinney, 58, and brother Emmett, 56, a captain at Fire Station 9 in the 
Florence area, left the construction trades and got started in what has become 
a family business back in 1959. 
</P>
<P>
"Our dad's brother was the district fire chief in Indianapolis for 36 years," 
John Kinney said, sitting down to a massive breakfast of fried eggs, potatoes, 
sausage and English muffins while his nephews toiled over the station house 
griddle. "Emmett and I have practically worked our whole careers in and around 
this area. I made captain in '69. Butch, when did you make it, '67?" 
</P>
<P>
"Sixty-six" Emmett Kinney answered. 
</P>
<P>
The brothers moved to southwest Los Angeles as young children. Their father, 
who operated knitting machines and made women's hosiery, left Indianapolis when 
strikebreakers defeated his efforts to organize garment workers, Emmett Kinney 
said. 
</P>
<P>
"We're working-class people, but that's changing," he said, explaining that his 
youngest son will enter Pepperdine Law School in the fall and his daughter is 
an opera singer in Belgium. 
</P>
<P>
None of John Kinney's children chose firefighting as a career, but Emmett's two 
other children followed their father and uncle into the County Fire Department. 
Joe, 27, joined seven years ago, and usually works in Huntington Park. Kevin, 
26, signed on in 1985 and works out of East Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
While the Kinneys all work within a few miles of one another, their homes are 
scattered all over Southern California: John lives in Mission Viejo, Emmett in 
Camarillo, Joe in Ontario and Kevin in Agoura Hills. 
</P>
<P>
Both Joe and Kevin say they won't push the next generation of Kinneys to follow 
in the family tradition. But they won't try to dissuade them either. 
</P>
<P>
"When I came into this, I had high expectations -- I always thought my dad had 
a great job," Kevin Kinney said. "And the job has exceeded my expectations. You 
never know day-to-day what you'll be doing." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, The Kinney family is certainly well-represented in the county Fire 
Department by, from left, John, his nephews Joe and Kevin and their father, 
Emmett. JIM HUDELSON / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
