<HEADLINE>
<P>
LIZ SMITH: HOPES ARISE FOR NEW EMERGENCE OF LIZA IN FILM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LIZ SMITH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIZA MINNELLI is off to Toronto in early September to begin a new film for 
Paramount titled "Stepping Out." In this one -- based on a British play -- Liza 
portrays a tap dance instructor. Lewis Gilbert will direct. Her co-stars are to 
be Shelley Winters, Ellen Greene, Andrea Martin and Bill Irwin. 
</P>
<P>
This is just great news. For as electrifying as Liza Minnelli is on stage, in 
concert, here is a woman made for the movies. It is unfortunate that Hollywood 
has never really known what to do with Liza's oversized talent. Only "Cabaret" 
for which she won the Oscar, and Martin Scorsese's "New York, New York" were 
able to showcase not only her dazzling musical abilities, but the sensitivity 
and wry humor of her acting. 
</P>
<P>
Perhaps the '90s will see a new emergence of Liza on screen. 
</P>
<P>
On the personal side, Liza has triumphed unconditionally. She fought her demons 
and won, becoming a role model of willpower and determination. This in the face 
of a press and public that perversely seemed to expect, no, demand that Liza 
self-destruct. She has made a great success of her marriage to sculptor Mark 
Gero, against daunting odds. It hasn't been 11 years of wedded bliss. It's been 
years of working overtime on a relationship that both of them obviously care 
about deeply. Neither one took the easy way out by throwing up their hands and 
saying, "I can't handle this!" They kept it together. For the strong and 
graceful handling of her personal life alone, Liza should take great and 
justifiable pride. 
</P>
<P>
Liza Minnelli in the '90s. The best is yet to be. 
</P>
<P>
MANDY PATINKIN, currently on screen in "Dick Tracy" as 88 Keys, will soon be 
back on stage. He's just been signed to star in Peter Hall's new musical "Born 
Again," based on the Eugene Ionesco play "Rhinoceros." "Born Again" opens in 
London this fall with an eye on Broadway for the summer 1991 season. 
</P>
<P>
Patinkin also has a new album from Columbia coming out around Christmas. It 
will include a number from William Finn's new musical "Falsettoland." 
</P>
<P>
DINAH SHORE, at a taping of her "Conversation With Dinah" TV show, recently 
asked veteran actor and fairly new author Kirk Douglas who he would like to 
have star in a movie version of his first book, the autobiography "The Ragman's 
Son." 
</P>
<P>
Kirk replied that ideally the film would involve his entire family: son Peter 
would produce, son Eric would play the "young" Kirk, and son Michael as the 
"midlife' Douglas. He'd play himself in more recent years. However, Kirk said 
he doesn't think he can afford Michael Douglas' salary, so maybe it won't be a 
family affair. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Liza Minelli 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
